me, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Holstein","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: habitational name from the province of Holstein, long disputed between Germany and Denmark. This gets its name from <i>holsten</i>, the dative plural, originally used after a preposition, of <i>holst</i>, from Middle Low German <i>holt-sate</i> ‘dweller in the woods’ (from Middle Low German <i>holt</i> ‘wood’ + <i>sate</i>, <i>sete</i> ‘tenant’). The final syllable has been erroneously altered by analogy with North German <i>Steen</i> ‘stone’, which in South German and standard German has the form <i>Stein</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Holstine","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Holstein  ."]},{"name":"Hulstein","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Gerrit, Albertus, Kees.","Dutch vowel variant of German   Holstein  ."]},{"name":"Hollstein","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Hans, Heinz, Klaus, Kurt, Otto, Ulrich.","German: variant of   Holstein  , or perhaps a habitational name from Hollstein on the Werra River."]},{"name":"Holst","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Jorgen, Erik, Vibeke, Anders, Carsten, Ludvig, Sven.","North German and Scandinavian: habitational name for someone from Holstein (see   Holstein  ), a derivative of German <i>Holtsate</i>, Danish <i>Holtsete</i> ‘person from Holstein’.","Dutch (also <b>Van Holst</b>): habitational name for someone from any of several places so called, from <i>holst, hulst</i> ‘holly (forest)’. Compare   Hulst  ."]},{"name":"Holsten","meanings":["North German: variant of   Holstein   or   Holst  ."]}]},{"name":"Adolf","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>Adelwolf</i>, a compound of <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>wolf</i> ‘wolf’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"(III.)","type":"LAST","a